♪ ♪

66
00:03:54,526 --> 00:03:57,195
[man over P.A.] Can we have
your attention, please?

67
00:03:57,196 --> 00:03:59,822
We are now arriving
into Athenry Station, Athenry.

68
00:03:59,823 --> 00:04:02,408
Would all passengers for
Athenry please disembark now.

69
00:04:02,409 --> 00:04:04,327
Thank you very much.

70
00:04:04,328 --> 00:04:06,412
[Paula] Aha.

71
00:04:06,413 --> 00:04:08,414
Back in the game.

72
00:04:08,415 --> 00:04:09,875
So long, Jolie.

73
00:04:11,585 --> 00:04:13,712
♪ ♪

74
00:04:14,755 --> 00:04:17,173
Hello. This is Paula.

75
00:04:17,174 --> 00:04:19,008
Hi. Thanks so much
for getting back to me.

76
00:04:19,009 --> 00:04:20,802
Yeah, I'm expecting
two packages, um,

77
00:04:20,803 --> 00:04:22,804
but can you send it
to the Dublin address,

78
00:04:22,805 --> 00:04:24,430
not the Galway one?

79
00:04:24,431 --> 00:04:26,892
They're both on the account;
I just checked the wrong one.

80
00:04:27,935 --> 00:04:30,061
Yeah, the Oxmantown Road one.

81
00:04:30,062 --> 00:04:31,562
Thanks. Thanks a million.

82
00:04:31,563 --> 00:04:33,481
Anyone for any tea or coffee?

83
00:04:33,482 --> 00:04:35,775
- Tea or coffee? Anyone?
- Yeah...

84
00:04:35,776 --> 00:04:38,152
- Uh, coffee? Tea?
- No? Nobody for tea or coffee?

85
00:04:38,153 --> 00:04:40,613
That's grand, no coffee, no tea.

86
00:04:40,614 --> 00:04:42,365
[sighs]

87
00:04:42,366 --> 00:04:44,117
This is crazy, right?

88
00:04:44,118 --> 00:04:45,827
Totally.

89
00:04:45,828 --> 00:04:48,162
They're talking about closing
down public transport now, too.

90
00:04:48,163 --> 00:04:49,664
Yeah, I just heard that.

91
00:04:49,665 --> 00:04:52,125
I'm sure things will return
to normal in a few days.

92
00:04:52,126 --> 00:04:53,209
Mm-hmm.

93
00:04:53,210 --> 00:04:54,502
You coming from NUI?

94
00:04:54,503 --> 00:04:56,337
- Yeah. How'd you guess?
- The, uh,

95
00:04:56,338 --> 00:04:58,214
the huge pile of
academic-looking books

96
00:04:58,215 --> 00:04:59,298
gave it away.

97
00:04:59,299 --> 00:05:01,718
Right. Correct, yeah.

98
00:05:01,719 --> 00:05:03,929
College shut down
yesterday morning, so...

99
00:05:05,097 --> 00:05:06,807
How about you?

100
00:05:07,850 --> 00:05:10,059
I work in tech
just outside of Galway.

101
00:05:10,060 --> 00:05:12,353
They've, uh, furloughed everyone
for two weeks.

102
00:05:12,354 --> 00:05:13,980
Jesus. So, where are you going?

103
00:05:13,981 --> 00:05:15,898
My brother's flat in Dublin.

104
00:05:15,899 --> 00:05:17,775
All of my flatmates
have moved home,

105
00:05:17,776 --> 00:05:20,069
so I didn't really want
to be stuck in Galway

106
00:05:20,070 --> 00:05:22,071
- if things really shut down.
- Me, neither.

107
00:05:22,072 --> 00:05:23,614
What's a party town
without people?

108
00:05:23,615 --> 00:05:25,033
Right.

109
00:05:25,034 --> 00:05:26,951
Mind you, my brother's
a complete pain in the ass,

110
00:05:26,952 --> 00:05:28,327
so I don't which is better.

111
00:05:28,328 --> 00:05:29,996
But he's company.

112
00:05:29,997 --> 00:05:32,790
[Paula] Invite him to your
mother's house, it's perfect.

113
00:05:32,791 --> 00:05:35,334
Shut up. You just met him,
like, two minutes ago.

114
00:05:35,335 --> 00:05:37,879
Yeah, and it's going so well.

115
00:05:37,880 --> 00:05:39,964
God, you're lonely.

116
00:05:39,965 --> 00:05:41,049
- So...
- Where are you staying?

117
00:05:41,050 --> 00:05:43,427
- Sorry.
- Sorry. Uh, you go ahead.

118
00:05:44,470 --> 00:05:47,263
What does "in tech"
actually mean?

119
00:05:47,264 --> 00:05:49,223
I mean,
it's something I hear a lot,

120
00:05:49,224 --> 00:05:51,684
but I just kind of
nod along, but...

121
00:05:51,685 --> 00:05:53,352
So, I work for a company
that targets advertising

122
00:05:53,353 --> 00:05:55,021
- for produce companies.
- Oh, cool.

123
00:05:55,022 --> 00:05:58,191
- So you work in advertising.
- No. I-I work in tech.

124
00:05:58,192 --> 00:05:59,817
I handle
six or seven companies' accounts

125
00:05:59,818 --> 00:06:00,985
and work with them finding

126
00:06:00,986 --> 00:06:02,445
target consumers
for their brands,

127
00:06:02,446 --> 00:06:04,072
so they don't waste their time

128
00:06:04,073 --> 00:06:06,783
advertising to people who are
never gonna buy their products.

129
00:06:06,784 --> 00:06:10,411
Uh, we run algorithms based on
tracking consumer preferences,

130
00:06:10,412 --> 00:06:12,997
try to forecast
and model their actions.

131
00:06:12,998 --> 00:06:14,583
What about you?

132
00:06:15,626 --> 00:06:17,377
I'm a medievalist.

133
00:06:18,420 --> 00:06:19,505
Right.

134
00:06:20,547 --> 00:06:22,632
They didn't do so much of that
back then.

135
00:06:22,633 --> 00:06:25,384
Well, their, uh, their
processors were just too slow.

136
00:06:25,385 --> 00:06:26,512
[laughs softly]

137
00:06:27,596 --> 00:06:29,180
Sorry, uh, do you mind,

138
00:06:29,181 --> 00:06:31,349
I'm just getting a crick
in my neck at this angle.

139
00:06:31,350 --> 00:06:32,850
- Is it okay if I, uh...
- Yeah. Sorry.

140
00:06:32,851 --> 00:06:33,852
Go ahead.

141
00:06:38,816 --> 00:06:41,025
[exhales] Ah. That's better.

142
00:06:41,026 --> 00:06:43,362
What were you saying?

143
00:06:44,988 --> 00:06:47,407
Can't remember. Sorry.

144
00:06:48,450 --> 00:06:50,868
- Can I ask you
a funny question?
- Sure.

145
00:06:50,869 --> 00:06:54,622
When you first got on, how come
you sat over there with her,

146
00:06:54,623 --> 00:06:56,332
when you had the option
of the two tables?

147
00:06:56,333 --> 00:06:58,126
I just prefer to sit facing
the direction we're going in.

148
00:06:58,127 --> 00:06:59,335
That's all.

149
00:06:59,336 --> 00:07:02,046
Now you're sitting
the opposite way.

150
00:07:02,047 --> 00:07:03,339
Yeah, but I'm facing you.

151
00:07:03,340 --> 00:07:05,174
So my neurosis can
take a back seat for a bit.

152
00:07:05,175 --> 00:07:07,343
It's not a big thing.
Just a little quirk.

153
00:07:07,344 --> 00:07:10,304
It's not like it dominates
my life or anything.

154
00:07:10,305 --> 00:07:11,848
Do you want to swap seats?

155
00:07:11,849 --> 00:07:12,890
Yes.

156
00:07:12,891 --> 00:07:14,893
♪ ♪

157
00:07:20,983 --> 00:07:23,651
[exhales]

158
00:07:23,652 --> 00:07:27,488
Uh, so, where are you staying
till college reopens?

159
00:07:27,489 --> 00:07:29,282
- Uh, my mum's house.
- Uh-huh.

160
00:07:29,283 --> 00:07:31,367
You say that
with a hint of anxiety.

161
00:07:31,368 --> 00:07:34,954
Yeah, I've just loved being away
for the last few years,

162
00:07:34,955 --> 00:07:38,082
so the idea of going back
for a couple of weeks...

163
00:07:38,083 --> 00:07:40,084
I love her,
but she's one of those people

164
00:07:40,085 --> 00:07:42,171
you have to physically ask
to stop talking.

165
00:07:43,338 --> 00:07:44,505
Plus, she doesn't have a TV.

166
00:07:44,506 --> 00:07:46,883
- What? Really?
- Yeah. No Wi-Fi, either.

167
00:07:46,884 --> 00:07:48,676
- You're gonna kill yourself.
- Yup.

168
00:07:48,677 --> 00:07:49,927
Yup. She just...

169
00:07:49,928 --> 00:07:52,013
paints, writes poetry
and listens to the radio

170
00:07:52,014 --> 00:07:54,098
and tends to her indoor plants.

171
00:07:54,099 --> 00:07:55,017
She sounds brilliant.

172
00:07:55,018 --> 00:07:57,143
She kind of is.

173
00:07:57,144 --> 00:07:59,729
- Plus, she smokes grass.
- No way.

174
00:07:59,730 --> 00:08:01,856
- Yeah.
- She sounds a little
like my brother.

175
00:08:01,857 --> 00:08:03,858
Without all the painting,
poetry or...

176
00:08:03,859 --> 00:08:05,735
any of the creativity at all.

177
00:08:05,736 --> 00:08:08,362
- Really? Bit of a stoner?
- He's like Snoop Dogg

178
00:08:08,363 --> 00:08:10,031
and all
of Seth Rogen's performances

179
00:08:10,032 --> 00:08:11,866
in all of his movies
rolled into one...

180
00:08:11,867 --> 00:08:14,285
- big joint.
- I'd definitely like
to meet him.

181
00:08:14,286 --> 00:08:15,620
I don't know if you'd get along.

182
00:08:15,621 --> 00:08:17,247
Your mum might, though.

183
00:08:18,540 --> 00:08:21,209
♪ ♪

184
00:08:21,210 --> 00:08:23,586
So, how long do you think
this thing is liable to last?

185
00:08:23,587 --> 00:08:26,005
I think seminars
are going back on the 28th,

186
00:08:26,006 --> 00:08:27,215
so couple of weeks.

187
00:08:27,216 --> 00:08:29,675
So, you're a big reader?

188
00:08:29,676 --> 00:08:31,552
Yeah.

189
00:08:31,553 --> 00:08:33,387
Tell me about medievalism.

190
00:08:33,388 --> 00:08:35,431
- Like, in one sentence?
- Sure.

191
00:08:35,432 --> 00:08:37,391
God, you'd know you work
in advertising.

192
00:08:37,392 --> 00:08:39,227
I don't. I work in tech.

193
00:08:39,228 --> 00:08:42,230
I don't think I can even begin
to explain what medievalism is

194
00:08:42,231 --> 00:08:44,232
in one train ride,
let alone one sentence.

195
00:08:44,233 --> 00:08:46,567
- That's okay.
- It doesn't want
to be described.

196
00:08:46,568 --> 00:08:49,862
- I get it.
- You like things that
fit in neatly, right?

197
00:08:49,863 --> 00:08:52,657
I guess I do. Big Tetris fan.

198
00:08:52,658 --> 00:08:55,117
Mm. Well, I like things
that can't be explained,

199
00:08:55,118 --> 00:08:57,578
that just go on and on,
like an onion.

200
00:08:57,579 --> 00:09:00,206
- Yeah, but onions end.
- Like a really big onion, then.

201
00:09:00,207 --> 00:09:02,041
One that would take
my whole life

202
00:09:02,042 --> 00:09:03,709
just to write the prologue to.

203
00:09:03,710 --> 00:09:05,336
I like that.

204
00:09:05,337 --> 00:09:07,171
I don't like getting
to the ends of things.

205
00:09:07,172 --> 00:09:09,173
I'm the exact opposite.

206
00:09:09,174 --> 00:09:11,050
Show me how it works,
what it's called,

207
00:09:11,051 --> 00:09:13,469
how it fits in, and I don't...
I don't need to know

208
00:09:13,470 --> 00:09:15,554
anything else.
I don't have a scholarly mind.

209
00:09:15,555 --> 00:09:18,183
I fall asleep at anything deeper
than Malcolm Gladwell.

210
00:09:19,226 --> 00:09:22,061
Well, still,
I'm glad you sat here.

211
00:09:22,062 --> 00:09:23,646
Really?

212
00:09:23,647 --> 00:09:25,898
Yeah. You're way better
than the serial killer.

213
00:09:25,899 --> 00:09:27,109
Who?

214
00:09:29,945 --> 00:09:33,365
[strings play
horror movie sting]

215
00:09:34,408 --> 00:09:36,450
No, Paula.

216
00:09:36,451 --> 00:09:38,494
I'm the serial killer.

217
00:09:38,495 --> 00:09:40,454
What?

218
00:09:40,455 --> 00:09:41,831
It's me.

219
00:09:41,832 --> 00:09:43,291
This is a horror,

220
00:09:43,292 --> 00:09:46,294
not a romance.

221
00:09:46,295 --> 00:09:48,880
You should have sat
next to someone else.

222
00:09:51,341 --> 00:09:53,718
Okay, you're way too good
at that.

223
00:09:53,719 --> 00:09:55,095
Sorry.

224
00:09:56,138 --> 00:09:58,180
How do you know my name?

225
00:09:58,181 --> 00:10:00,892
You mentioned it on the phone.

226
00:10:01,935 --> 00:10:04,229
Didn't realize
you were paying attention.

227
00:10:05,564 --> 00:10:08,524
And who said anything
about a romance?

228
00:10:08,525 --> 00:10:10,444
[gentle guitar music playing]

229
00:10:14,448 --> 00:10:16,324
Sorry, is this bothering you?

230
00:10:16,325 --> 00:10:18,952
- No.
- Go ahead.

231
00:10:19,995 --> 00:10:22,913
♪ You look so happy ♪

232
